layout.p: The manuscript is written in long lines. In the older part the number of lines per page varies from 13-16, in the younger part it varies from 8-17. The older part of the MS has rubrics in red. The versos of the fly-leaves and pp. 88-91 are blank.

handNote.p: pp. 2-29:3, 30-31:2, 31:7-13 is written in an practiced Icelandic Gothic bookhand from the fourteenth century.

pp. 29:4-14, 31:3-7, 31:13-15, containing Icelandic epilogues for the Latin prayers, is written in a second hand. It is also a practiced Icelandic Gothic bookhand from the fourteenth like the first, yet the writing is smaller and more neat.

Page 32, containing an incomplete Icelandic prayer, is written in a third hand. According to Christopher Sanders this hand is from the sixteenth century. It is an Icelandic Gothic bookhand resembling the first hand the most, but the writing is more casual.
The younger part of the manuscript: pp. 33-87 and 92 is written in an Icelandic New-Gothic hand.

decoNote.p: Page 1 contains a full length picture of Saint Margrét. She is standing under a trefoiled arch, with a crown on her head, and the hair falling down over her shoulders, in flowing drapery, and with a book in her left hand, in the right a sword whose point pierces the dragon under her feet. The picture has been coloured and tampered with in later ages.
The initials of the older part of the manuscript are in red and blue.
The initials of the younger part of the manuscript are exuberantly flourished in red and gilt.

accMat.p: An AM-slip pasted on the first fly-leaf reads: Fra Jon Haldorsen i Hiterdal annammet med Buudeskib 1728. den 10. Julii. Var þä innbunded, enn eg tok banded af.

origin.p: The manuscript is written in Iceland. According to Kristian Kålund ( KKKat ) it consists of two parts: an older and a younger. The older is from the fourteenth century (pp. 1-32), and the younger is from the seventeenth century (the fly-leaves and pp. 33-87 and 92). .

provenance.p:
According to a note on page 92 the manuscript once belonged to the Priest Þorkell Guðbjartsson and afterwards to Bishop Jón Arason and after him to his daughter Helga Aradóttir. Presumably their names written were on the last page of the codex before it was rebound in 1689 . The note, written in the seventeenth century-writer's hand, says: þessa Bok Hefur Att Adur
Sira Þorkell Gudbiartzson og
Sydar Effter Hann Jon Biskup Ara
son Huoria Eygnadest Sydan
Helga Ara Dotter og voru allra þe
szra Nofn a Sydasta blada A Bok
enne Adur hun var uppbundenn.
Anno 1689 þann 27 Decembris
JSsmeh. The next known owner is the Priest Jón Halldórsson of Hítardalur.

acquisition.p: According to the AM-slip Árni Magnússon got the codex from the Priest Jón Halldórsson of Hítardalur in : Fra Hr. Jon Haldorsen i Hiterdal annammet med Buudeskib 1728. den 10. Julii. Var þä innbunded, enn eg tok banded af.
